# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: natural-resources-defense-council
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/1970-in-the-environment] This is a list of notable events relating to the environment in 1970.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/1970-in-the-environment] They relate to environmental law, conservation, environmentalism and environmental issues.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] A **501(c)(3) organization** is a United States corporation, trust, unincorporated association, or other type of organization exempt from federal income tax under section 501(c)(3) of Title 26 of the United States Code.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] It is one of the 29 types of 501(c) nonprofit organizations in the U.S.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] The 501(c)(3) exemption applies also for any non-incorporated community chest, fund, cooperating association or foundation organized and operated exclusively for those purposes.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] There are also supporting organizations—often referred to in shorthand form as *Friends of* organizations.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] 26 U.S.C. § 170 provides a deduction for federal income tax purposes, for some donors who make charitable contributions to most types of 501(c)(3) organizations, among others.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Regulations specify which such deductions must be verifiable to be allowed (e.g., receipts for donations of $250 or more).
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] The basic requirement of obtaining tax-exempt status is that the organization is specifically limited in powers to purposes that the IRS classifies as tax-exempt purposes.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] This limiting of the powers is crucial to obtaining tax exempt status with the IRS and then on the state level.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Organizations acquire 501(c)(3) tax exemption by filing IRS Form 1023.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] As of 2006, the form must be accompanied by an $850 filing fee if the yearly gross receipts for the organization are expected to average $10,000 or more.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] If yearly gross receipts are expected to average less than $10,000, the filing fee is reduced to $400.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] The IRS released a software tool called Cyber Assistant in 2013, which was succeeded by Form 1023-EZ in 2014.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] There is an alternative way for an organization to obtain status if an organization has applied for a determination and either there is an actual controversy regarding a determination or the Internal Revenue Service has failed to make a determination.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Prior to December 30, 1969, nonprofit organizations could declare themselves to be tax-exempt under Section 501(c)(3) without first obtaining Internal Revenue Service recognition by filing Form 1023 and receiving a determination letter.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] A nonprofit organization that did so prior to that date could still be subject to challenge of its status by the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] An individual may not take a tax deduction on gifts made to a 501(c)(3) organization that is organized and operated exclusively for the testing for public safety.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] In the case of tuition fees paid to a private 501(c)(3) school or a church school, the payments are not tax-deductible charitable contributions because they are payments for services rendered to the payee or the payee's children.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] The payments are not tax-deductible charitable contributions even if a significant portion of a church school's curriculum is religious education.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] For a payment to be a tax-deductible charitable contribution, it must be a voluntary transfer of money or other property with no expectation of procuring financial benefit equal to the transfer amount.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Before donating to a 501(c)(3) organization, a donor can consult the searchable online IRS list of charitable organizations to verify that the organization qualifies to receive tax-deductible charitable contributions.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Consumers may file IRS Form 13909, with documentation, to complain about inappropriate or fraudulent (i.e., fundraising, political campaigning, lobbying) activities by any 501(c)(3) organization.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Most 501(c)(3) must disclose the names and addresses of certain large donors to the Internal Revenue Service on their annual returns, but this information is not required to be made available to the public, unless the organization is an independent foundation.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Churches are generally exempt from this reporting requirement.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Every 501(c)(3) organization must make available for public inspection its application for tax-exemption, including its Form 1023 or Form 1023-EZ and any attachments, supporting documents, and follow-up correspondence with the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Annual returns must be publicly available for a three-year period beginning with the due date of the return, including any extension of time for filing.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] The Internal Revenue Service provides information about specific 501(c)(3) organizations through its Tax Exempt Organization Search online.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] A private nonprofit organization, GuideStar, provides information on 501(c)(3) organizations.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] ProPublica's Nonprofit Explorer provides copies of each organization's Form 990 and, for some organizations, audited financial statements.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] WikiCharities, is a nonprofit database of nonprofits and charities by name, location, and topic, that allows each organization to report its financials, leadership, contacts, and other activities.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] However, Open990 was a searchable database of information about organizations that had to shut down due to IRS delays in posting information online.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Section 501(c)(3) organizations are prohibited from supporting political candidates, as a result of the Johnson Amendment enacted in 1954.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Section 501(c)(3) organizations are subject to limits on lobbying, having a choice between two sets of rules establishing an upper bound for their lobbying activities.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Section 501(c)(3) organizations risk loss of their tax-exempt status if these rules are violated.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] An organization that loses its 501(c)(3) status due to being engaged in political activities cannot subsequently qualify for 501(c)(3) status.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] As a result, it is common for 501(c)(3) organizations to have affiliated nonprofits that are classified as 501(c)(4) organizations, allowing the affiliate to engage in political activity without threatening 501(c)(3) status.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Churches must meet specific requirements to obtain and maintain tax-exempt status; these are outlined in "IRS Publication 1828: Tax Guide for Churches and Religious Organizations".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] This guide outlines activities allowed and not allowed by churches under the 501(c)(3) designation.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Schools for the preparation of its ministers.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Having an established congregation served by an organized ministry is of central importance.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Points 4, 6, 8, 11, 12, and 13 are also especially important.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Nevertheless, the 14-point list is a guideline; it is not intended to be all-encompassing, and other facts and circumstances may be relevant factors.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Although there is no definitive definition of a church for Internal Revenue Code purposes, in 1986 the United States Tax Court said that "A church is a coherent group of individuals and families that join together to accomplish the religious purposes of mutually held beliefs.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] The United States Tax Court has stated that, while a church can certainly broadcast its religious services by radio, radio broadcasts themselves do not constitute a congregation unless there is a group of people physically attending those religious services.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] A church can conduct worship services in various specific locations rather than in one official location.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] A church may have a significant number of people associate themselves with the church on a regular basis, even if the church does not have a traditional established list of individual members.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] In order to qualify as a tax-exempt church, church activities must be a significant part of the organization's operations.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] An organization whose operations include a substantial nonexempt commercial purposes, such as operating restaurants and grocery stores in a manner consistent with a particular religion's religious beliefs does not qualify as a tax-exempt church.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] In practice, hospital policies often don't cover outside contracted physicians or narrowly defined medically necessary services, leaving patients who technically qualify for charity care still responsible for significant medical bills.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Organizations described in section 501(c)(3) are prohibited from conducting political campaign activities to intervene in elections to public office.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Since section 501(c)(3)'s political-activity prohibition was enacted, "commentators and litigants have challenged the provision on numerous constitutional grounds", such as freedom of speech, vagueness, and equal protection and selective prosecution.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Historically, Supreme Court decisions, such as *Regan v.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Taxation with Representation of Washington*, suggested that the Court, if it were to squarely examine the political-activity prohibition of § 501(c)(3), would uphold it against a constitutional challenge.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] However, some have suggested that a successful challenge to the political activities prohibition of Section 501(c)(3) might be more plausible in light of *Citizens United v.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] In contrast to the prohibition on political campaign interventions by all section 501(c)(3) organizations, public charities (but not private foundations) may conduct a limited amount of lobbying to influence legislation.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Although the law states that "no substantial part" of a public charity's activities can go to lobbying, charities with large budgets may lawfully expend a million dollars (under the "expenditure" test) or more (under the "substantial part" test) per year on lobbying.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] The Internal Revenue Service has never defined the term "substantial part" with respect to lobbying.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] To establish a safe harbor for the "substantial part" test, the United States Congress enacted §501(h), called the Conable election after its author, Representative Barber Conable.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] The section establishes limits based on operating budget that a charity can use to determine if it meets the substantial test.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] This changes the prohibition against direct intervention in partisan contests only for lobbying.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] The organization is now presumed in compliance with the substantiality test if they work within the limits.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] The Conable election requires a charity to file a declaration with the IRS and file a functional distribution of funds spreadsheet with their Form 990.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] IRS form 5768 is required to make the Conable election.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to conduct some or all of its charitable activities outside the United States.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to award grants to foreign charitable organizations if the grants are intended for charitable purposes and the grant funds are subject to the 501(c)(3) organization's control.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Additional procedures are required of 501(c)(3) organizations that are private foundations.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] Donors' contributions to a 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible only if the contribution is for the use of the 501(c)(3) organization, and that the 501(c)(3) organization is not merely serving as an agent or conduit of a foreign charitable organization.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] The 501(c)(3) organization's management should review the grant application from the foreign organization, decide whether to award the grant based on the intended use of the funds, and require continuous oversight based on the use of funds.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] If the donor imposes a restriction or earmark that the contribution must be used for foreign activities, then the contribution is deemed to be for the foreign organization rather than the 501(c)(3) organization, and the contribution is not tax-deductible.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] The purpose of the grant to the foreign organization cannot include endorsing or opposing political candidates for elected office in any country.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-3-organization] If a 501(c)(3) organization sets up and controls a foreign subsidiary to facilitate charitable work in a foreign country, then donors' contributions to the 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible even if intended to fund the foreign charitable activities.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A **501(c) organization** is a nonprofit organization in the federal law of the United States according to Internal Revenue Code (26 U.S.C. § 501(c)).
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Such organizations are exempt from some federal income taxes.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Sections 503 through 505 set out the requirements for obtaining such exemptions.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Many states refer to Section 501(c) for definitions of organizations exempt from state taxation as well.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] 501(c) organizations can receive unlimited contributions from individuals, corporations, and unions.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] For example, a nonprofit organization may be tax-exempt under section 501(c)(3) if its primary activities are charitable, religious, educational, scientific, literary, testing for public safety, fostering amateur sports competition, or preventing cruelty to children or animals.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] According to the IRS Publication 557, in the *Organization Reference Chart* section, the following is an exact list of 501(c) organization types (29 in total) and their corresponding descriptions.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A 501(c) organization is subject to tax on its unrelated business income.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] For most organizations, an organization's activity generates unrelated business income if it is regularly carried on and it is not substantially related to furthering the exempt purpose of the organization.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Disposal of donated goods valued over $2,500, or acceptance of goods worth over $5,000 may trigger special filing and record-keeping requirements.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A 501(c) organization must maintain proper records and file certain annual or special-purpose tax returns, e.g., 26 U.S.C. § 6033 and 26 U.S.C. § 6050L.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Prior to 2008, an annual return was not generally required from an exempt organization with less than $25,000 in gross income yearly.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Since 2008, most organizations whose annual gross receipts are less than $50,000 must file an annual information return known as Form 990-N.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Form 990-N, Form 990, Form 990-EZ, and Form 990-PF must be submitted electronically.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Failure to file required returns such as Form 990 (Return of Organization Exempt From Income Tax) may result in fines of up to $250,000 per year.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Exempt or political organizations, excluding churches or similar religious entities, must make their returns, reports, notices, and exempt applications available for public inspection.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Form 4506-A also allows the public inspection or photocopying access to Form 1023 "Application for Recognition of Exemption" or Form 1024, Form 8871 "Political Organization Notice of Section 527 Status", and Form 8872 "Political Organization Report of Contribution and Expenditures".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Internet access to many organizations' 990 and some other forms are available through GuideStar.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Failure to file such timely returns and to make other specific information available to the public also is prohibited.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Between 2010 and 2017 the IRS revoked the nonprofit status of more than 760,000 nonprofit organizations for failing to file the 990 form.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The 501(c)(3) exemption also applies for any unincorporated community chest, fund, cooperating association, or foundation that is organized and operated exclusively for those purposes.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] There are also supporting organizations—often referred to in shorthand form as "Friends of" organizations.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] 26 U.S.C. § 170, provides a deduction, for federal income tax purposes, for some donors who make charitable contributions to most types of 501(c)(3) organizations, among others.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] On the other hand, public charities (but not private foundations) may conduct a limited amount of lobbying to influence legislation.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Although the law states that "No substantial part..." of a public charity's activities can go to lobbying, charities may register for a 501(h) election allowing them to lawfully conduct lobbying activities as long as their financial expenditure does not exceed a specified amount.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] 501(c)(3) organizations risk loss of tax exempt status if any of these rules are violated.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A **501(c)(4) organization** is a social welfare organization, such as a civic organization or a neighborhood association.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] An organization is considered by the IRS to be operated exclusively for the promotion of social welfare if it is primarily engaged in promoting the common good and general welfare of the people of the community.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Net earnings must be exclusively used for charitable, educational, or recreational purposes.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] 501(c)(4)s are similar to 501(c)(5)s and 501(c)(6)s in that the organizations may inform the public on controversial subjects and attempt to influence legislation relevant to its program.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Unlike 501(c)(3) organizations, they may also participate in political campaigns and elections, as long as their primary activity is the promotion of social welfare and related to the organization's purpose.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The income tax exemption for 501(c)(4) organizations applies to most of their operations, but income spent on political activities—generally the advocacy of a particular candidate in an election—is taxable.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] An "action" organization generally qualifies as a 501(c)(4) organization.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] An "action" organization is one whose activities substantially include, or are exclusively, direct or grassroots lobbying related to advocacy for or against legislation or proposing, supporting, or opposing legislation that is related to its purpose.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A 501(c)(4) organization may directly or indirectly support or oppose a candidate for public office as long as such activities are not a substantial amount of its activities.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A 501(c)(4) organization that lobbies must register with the Clerk of the House if it lobbies members of the House or their staff.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Likewise, a 501(c)(4) organization must register with the Secretary of the Senate if it lobbies members of the Senate or their staff.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] In addition, the 501(c)(4) organization must either inform its members the amount it spends on lobbying or pay a proxy tax to the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Lobbying expenses and political expenses are not deductible as business expenses.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Wisconsin Right to Life, Inc.*, in which the Supreme Court struck down the part of the McCain-Feingold Act that prohibited 501(c)(4)s, 501(c)(5)s, and 501(c)(6)s from broadcasting electioneering communications.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The Act defined an electioneering communication as a communication that mentions a candidate's name 60 days before a primary or 30 days before a general election.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Contributions to 501(c)(4) organizations are not tax-deductible as charitable donations unless the organization is either a volunteer fire department or a veterans organization.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Dues or contributions to 501(c)(4) organizations may be deductible as a business expense under IRC 162, although amounts paid for intervention or participation in any political campaign, direct lobbying, grass roots lobbying, and contact with certain federal officials are not deductible.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] If a 501(c)(4) engages in a substantial number of these activities, then only the amount of dues or contributions that can be attributed to other activities may be deductible as a business expense.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The organization must provide a notice to its members containing a reasonable estimate of the amount related to lobbying and political campaign expenditures, or else it is subject to a proxy tax on its lobbying and political campaign expenditures.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] It must also state that contributions to the organization are not deductible as charitable contributions during fundraising.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A 501(c)(4) organization is not required to disclose their donors publicly, with the exception of organizations that make independent expenditures as of 2018.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The former complete lack of disclosure led to extensive use of the 501(c)(4) provisions for organizations that are actively involved in lobbying, and has become controversial.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Criticized as "dark money", spending from these organizations on political advertisements has exceeded spending from Super PACs.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Spending by organizations that do not disclose their donors increased from less than $5.2 million in 2006 to well over $300 million during the 2012 election season.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The origins of 501(c)(4) organizations date back to the Revenue Act of 1913, which created a new group of tax-exempt organizations dedicated to social welfare in a precursor to what is now Internal Revenue Code Section 501(c)(4).
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The Protecting Americans from Tax Hikes Act of 2015 introduced a new requirement on 501(c)(4) organizations.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Within 60 days of the organization's formation, a 501(c)(4) organization is required to file Form 8976 with the Internal Revenue Service as notification that it is operating as a section 501(c)(4) organization.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The Internal Revenue Service will acknowledge receipt of the notification, but the acknowledgment is not a determination that the organization qualifies for section 501(c)(4) tax-exempt status.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A 501(c)(4) organization is not required to send the notification if the organization was formed on or before July 8, 2016, and it either applied for a determination letter using Form 1024 or filed a Form 990 between December 19, 2015, and July 8, 2016.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] As of January 2018, the application for recognition of exemption as a 501(c)(4) organization is a new form, Form 1024-A, rather than Form 1024.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] In 2017 revocations of 501(c)(4) groups comprised 58% which usually is only 15% of the total nonprofits which have their tax status revoked by the IRS for their failure to file Form 990.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A **501(c)(5) organization** is a labor organization, an agricultural organization, or a horticultural organization.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Labor unions, county fairs, and flower societies are examples of these types of groups.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Labor union organizations were a primary benefactor of this organization type, dating to the 19th century.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] According to the Internal Revenue Service, a 501(c)(5) organization has a duty of providing service to its members first.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The organization's benefits may not inure to a specific member, but the rules for inurement vary among the three different types of organizations under this segment.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A 501(c)(5) organization can make unlimited corporate, individual, or union contributions.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A labor organization may pay benefits to its members because paying benefits improves all members' shared working conditions.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] An agricultural organization can provide financial assistance to its members in order to improve the conditions of those engaged in agricultural pursuits generally.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Members can benefit in incidental ways from the organization's exempt activities as long as the benefits are available to all persons.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The first exemption for labor organizations from corporate income tax was enacted as part of the Payne–Aldrich Tariff Act of 1909.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The Revenue Act of 1913 excluded "labor, agricultural, or horticultural organizations" from income tax liability.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Much like 501(c)(4) and 501(c)(6) organizations, 501(c)(5) organizations may also perform some political activities.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] 501(c)(5) organizations are allowed to attempt to influence legislation that is related to the common union interests of its members.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] 501(c)(5) organizations can receive unlimited contributions from corporations, individuals, and labor unions.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The names and addresses of contributors are not required to be made available for public inspection.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] All other information, including the amount of contributions, the description of noncash contributions, and any other information, is required to be made available for public inspection unless it clearly identifies the contributor.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A union membership dues paid to a 501(c)(5) organization are generally an ordinary and necessary business expense.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The membership dues are tax-deductible in full unless a substantial part of the 501(c)(5) organization's activities consists of political activity, in which case a tax deduction is allowed only for the portion of membership dues that are for other activities.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The Federal Election Commission is required to enforce this provision based on a federal court decision in 2018.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A **501(c)(6) organization** is a business league, a chamber of commerce like the U.S.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A business league may qualify if it is an association of persons having a common business interest, whose purpose is to promote the common business interest and whose activities improve business conditions rather than actually conduct the business itself.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Members of the organization must be of the same trade, business, occupation, or profession in order to qualify.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A local chamber of commerce or board of trade could qualify for similar reasons except that they may promote the common economic interests of all the commercial enterprises in a given trade or community.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] In order to qualify for a tax-exemption under section 501(c)(6), the organization must specify that it seeks to promote and improve business condition for a specific type of business.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Improving business conditions for *all* types of businesses is not generally qualifying.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Similarly, providing a service for a specific type of business is also not typically qualifying, as that would usually be more of a commercial enterprise.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] For example, the service of managing health insurance plans for its member businesses is often a commercial enterprise if it is not substantially related to improving the business conditions for specific lines of businesses.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] An association that promotes the common interests of certain hobbyists would not qualify because the Internal Revenue Service does not consider hobbies to be activities conducted as businesses.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] An organization whose primary activity is advertising the products or services of its members does not qualify because the organization is performing a service for its members rather than promoting common interests.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] If an organization's primary activity is advertising the products or services of its members' industry as a whole, however, the organization will generally qualify if it also performs other services for its members.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Much like 501(c)(4) and 501(c)(5) organizations, 501(c)(6) organizations may also perform some political activities.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] 501(c)(6) organizations are allowed to attempt to influence legislation that is related to the common business interests of its members.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A 501(c)(6) organization may receive unlimited contributions from corporations, individuals, and labor unions.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The names and addresses of contributors are not required to be made available for public inspection, with the exception of a 501(c)(6) organization that makes independent expenditures.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] All other information, including the amount of contributions, the description of non-cash contributions, and any other information, is required to be made available for public inspection unless it clearly identifies the contributor.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Chamber of Commerce is a large political spender, and Freedom Partners used its status as a 501(c)(6) organization to raise and distribute over $250 million during the 2012 election campaigns without disclosing its donors.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The group's existence was not publicly known until nearly a year after the election.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A business's membership dues paid to a 501(c)(6) organization are generally an ordinary and necessary business expense.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The membership dues are tax-deductible in full unless a substantial part of the 501(c)(6) organization's activities consists of political activity, in which case a tax deduction is allowed only for the portion of membership dues that are for other activities.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The predecessor of IRC 501(c)(6) was enacted as part of the Revenue Act of 1913 likely due to a U.S.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Chamber of Commerce request for an exemption for nonprofit "civic" and "commercial" organizations, which resulted in IRC 501(c)(4) for nonprofit "civic" organizations and IRC 501(c)(6) for nonprofit "commercially-oriented" organizations.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The Revenue Act of 1928 amended the statute to include real estate boards.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] In 1966, professional football leagues were added to the described organizations.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] IRC 501(c)(6) amendment was enacted in 1966 to ensure that a professional football league's exemption would not be jeopardized because it administered a players' pension fund.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Additionally, a professional sports league's exemption is not to be jeopardized because its primary source of revenue is the sale of television broadcasting rights to its games because the broadcasting of games increases public awareness of the sport.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] In 2013, Senator Tom Coburn introduced legislation to disallow a tax exemption for the National Football League, the Professional Golfers' Association of America, and other professional sports organizations.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Coburn estimated the tax exemption cost $100 million, but he said he could not get other members of Congress to support the legislation.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A **501(c)(7) organization** is a social or recreational club that is organized for pleasure, recreation, and other nonprofitable purposes.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Members must share interests and have a common goal directed toward pleasure and recreation, and the organization must provide opportunities for personal contact among members.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The organization's facilities and services must be open to its members and their guests only.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The organization must be a club of individuals, and no individual may derive profit from the organization's net earnings.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Examples include college alumni associations; college fraternities or college sororities operating chapter houses for students; country clubs; amateur sport clubs; supper clubs that provide a meeting place, library, and dining room for members; hobby clubs; and garden clubs.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A substantial amount of the 501(c)(7) organization's activities must be related to social and recreational activities for its members.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] No more than 35 percent of its gross receipts may derive from non-members, and no more than 15 percent of its gross receipts is permitted to come from use of its facilities or services by the general public.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] An organization that exceeds these limits may lose its 501(c)(7) status.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Similarly, if at least 75 percent of a group using club facilities are members of the organization, the Internal Revenue Service will assume the nonmembers are the guests of the member, and the revenue is deemed to be derived from the member.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] It is the responsibility of the organization to maintain these records.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] If the organization does not keep sufficient records to link revenue to a member, the Internal Revenue Service assumes the revenue came from a nonmember.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The organization is subject to Unrelated Business Income Tax for the revenue derived from nonmember use of its facilities and services, less allowable deductions.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] If the organization sells assets that were previously used for recreational or social purposes, the proceeds are considered related business income as long as the proceeds are reinvested in the organization.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Public use of the organization's facilities must be minimal, generally either less than $2,500 per year or less than five percent of its total gross receipts from normal and usual activities of the club.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A 501(c)(7) organization cannot have a written policy of discriminating on the basis of race, color, or religion.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Nevertheless, a 501(c)(7) organization is permitted to limit its members to a particular religion in order to further the teachings of that religion.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] An auxiliary of a 501(c)(8) fraternal benefit society that limits membership to members of a particular religion is allowed to do so as well.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Having written policies that limit its membership by ethnic origin and gender would not jeopardize the organization's tax-exempt status.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Congress justified the tax-exemption with the reasoning that the members join to provide themselves with recreational or social organization without further tax consequences, similar as if they had paid for the benefits directly.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Tax-exemption was available for organizations operated exclusively for pleasure, recreation, and other nonprofitable purposes.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] In 1969, Congress passed a law stating that social and recreational clubs were permitted to engage in some unrelated business income, subject to income tax.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A **501(c)(8) organization** is a fraternal benefit society.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The society must have members of a similar calling, recreation, or profession, or members who work together to accomplish a worthy goal.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The members have associated themselves in order to help each other and to promote the common cause.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The society must have written documentation of its eligibility standards for membership, classes of membership, a process of admission, and rights and privileges of members.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The members must have a common bond, which may be based on religious beliefs, gender, occupation, ethnicity, or shared values.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The society must have a supreme governing body and subordinate lodges into which members are elected, initiated, or admitted in accordance with its laws.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The supreme governing body should be composed of delegates elected directly by members or intermediate assemblies.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The society must offer benefits to members, which may include life insurance, medical insurance, scholarships, educational programs, travel opportunities, and discount programs.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Revenue generated from providing benefits to non-members must be insubstantial to the society and may be taxable as unrelated business income.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Fraternal benefit societies trace their lineage back through mutual benefit societies, friendly societies and eventually to medieval guilds.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Many fraternal benefit societies were founded to serve the needs of immigrants and other under-served groups who shared common bonds of religion, ethnicity, gender, occupation or shared values.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Section 38 of the Payne–Aldrich Tariff Act of 1909 was the first law to provide a tax-exemption for fraternal beneficiary societies.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The tax-exemption was later codified as section 501(c)(8) with the Internal Revenue Code of 1954.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Similar to 501(c)(8) organizations, 501(c)(10) organizations are also fraternal societies, orders, or associations operating under the lodge system, but 501(c)(10) organizations do not offer life, sick, accident, or other benefits.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] 501(c)(10) organizations devote net earnings exclusively to religious, charitable, scientific, literary, educational, and fraternal purposes.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A **501(c)(13)** organization is a certain type of cemetery company.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] There are two primary types of eligible cemetery companies.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A mutual cemetery company must be either "owned by and operated exclusively for the benefit of its lot owners who hold such lots for bona fide burial purposes and not for the purpose of resale" or engages in the burial of impoverished people performing similar charitable activities.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A nonprofit cemetery corporation must be incorporated solely for the purpose of the burial or the cremation of bodies and no part of its net earnings inures to the benefit of any private shareholder or individual.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Any net gain by the cemetery must be devoted to certain cemetery functions, such as the cemetery's operations, maintenance, and improvements; acquisition of cemetery property; and investment of the net gain in order to provide additional income for cemetery functions.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Net gains are not allowed to be distributed to individuals.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A perpetual care fund that is used by a profit-making cemetery to maintain cemetery properties and burial lots is not eligible under 501(c)(13).
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] On the other hand, a nonprofit organization may have a perpetual care fund without jeopardizing its exemption under Section 501(c)(13).
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A cemetery that owns or operates a morgue, whether on its own grounds or elsewhere, is not eligible under 501(c)(13) because the Internal Revenue Service does not consider mortuary services necessarily incident to burial purposes.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The provision of traditional burial services that directly support and maintain basic tenets and beliefs of a religion regarding burial of its members" may still be eligible under 501(c)(13).
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A cemetery that buries animals is not eligible under 501(c)(13).
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] A cemetery company wishing to be recognized under Section 501(c)(13) needs to prepare and file Form 1024 with the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Charitable contributions to a 501(c)(13) organization are tax-deductible to the donor.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Payments for perpetual care of a particular lot or a particular crypt are not considered tax-deductible charitable contributions.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Payments made as part of the purchase price of a burial lot or crypt are not considered tax-deductible charitable contributions, even if a portion of the payment is for the perpetual care of the entirety of the cemetery.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Bequests or gifts to a 501(c)(13) cemetery are not deductible for federal estate tax purposes or gift tax purposes.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] Historically, cemeteries were exempt from local property taxes and excise taxes in most states because states generally considered cemeteries to be performing a recognized civic service.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] The Tariff Act of 1913 provided an exemption from federal income taxes for mutual cemetery companies that were organized and operated exclusively "for the benefit of their members".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] In 1921, Congress extended the tax-exemption to cemetery companies that are not mutual and to cemetery companies that are not operated for profit as well as any corporation solely incorporated to operate a cemetery and whose net gains do not inure to any person.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/501-c-4] In 1970, Congress added crematorium in the definition of cemetery for the purposes of Section 501(c)(13).
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Acrylonitrile is one of the components of ABS plastic (acrylonitrile butadiene styrene).
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Acrylonitrile was first synthesized by the French chemist Charles Moureu in 1893.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Acrylonitrile is produced by catalytic ammoxidation of propylene, also known as the SOHIO process.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] In 2002, world production capacity was estimated at 5 million tonnes per year, rising to about 6 million tonnes by 2017.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Acetonitrile and hydrogen cyanide are significant byproducts that are recovered for sale.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] In fact, the 2008–2009 acetonitrile shortage was caused by a decrease in demand for acrylonitrile.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] In the SOHIO process, propylene, ammonia, and air (oxidizer) are passed through a fluidized bed reactor containing the catalyst at 400–510 °C and 50–200 kPag.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] The reactants pass through the reactor only once, before being quenched in aqueous sulfuric acid.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Excess propylene, carbon monoxide, carbon dioxide, and dinitrogen that do not dissolve are vented directly to the atmosphere, or are incinerated.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] The aqueous solution consists of acrylonitrile, acetonitrile, hydrocyanic acid, and ammonium sulfate (from excess ammonia).
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] A recovery column removes bulk water, and acrylonitrile and acetonitrile are separated by distillation.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] One of the first useful catalysts was bismuth phosphomolybdate (Bi9PMo12O52) supported on silica.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Further improvements have since been made.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Various green chemistry routes to acrylonitrile are being explored from renewable feedstocks, such as lignocellulosic biomass, glycerol (from biodiesel production), or glutamic acid (which can itself be produced from renewable feedstocks).
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] The lignocellulosic route involves fermentation of the biomass to propionic acid and 3-hydroxypropionic acid, which are then converted to acrylonitrile by dehydration and ammoxidation.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] The glycerol route begins with its dehydration to acrolein, which undergoes ammoxidation to give acrylonitrile.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] The glutamic acid route employs oxidative decarboxylation to 3-cyanopropanoic acid, followed by a decarbonylation-elimination to acrylonitrile.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Of these, the glycerol route is broadly considered to be the most viable, although none of these green methods are commercially competitive.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Hydrolysis with sulfuric acid gives acrylamide sulfate, CH=CHC(O)NH2·H2SO4.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] This salt can be converted to acrylamide and to methyl acrylate.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Hydrogenation of acrylonitrile is one route to propionitrile.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Typical protic nucleophiles are alcohols, thiols, and especially amines.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] When hydrogen cyanide is used the product is succinonitrile.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Acrylonitrile and derivatives, such as 2-chloroacrylonitrile, are dienophiles in Diels–Alder reactions.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Acrylonitrile is toxic with LD50 = 81 mg/kg (rats).
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] The burning material releases fumes of hydrogen cyanide and oxides of nitrogen.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] It is classified as a Class 1 carcinogen (carcinogenic) by the International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC), and workers exposed to high levels of airborne acrylonitrile are diagnosed more frequently with lung cancer than the rest of the population.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Acrylonitrile appears to cause oxidative stress and oxidative DNA damage.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Acrylonitrile increases cancer in high dose tests in male and female rats and mice and induces apoptosis in human umbilical cord mesenchymal stem cells.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] It evaporates quickly at room temperature (20 °C) to reach dangerous concentrations; skin irritation, respiratory irritation, and eye irritation are the immediate effects of this exposure.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Pathways of exposure for humans include emissions, auto exhaust, and cigarette smoke that can expose the human subject directly if they inhale or smoke.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Routes of exposure include inhalation, oral, and to a certain extent dermal uptake (tested with volunteer humans and in rat studies).
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Repeated exposure causes skin sensitization and may cause central nervous system and liver damage.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Acrylonitrile is excretion in urine as a conjugate to glutathione.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Some acrylonitrile is enzymatically converted into 2-cyanoethylene oxide, which produces cyanide and thiocyanate, which also are excreted in urine.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Exposure can thus be detected via blood draws and urine sampling.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] In July 2024, the International Agency for Research on Cancer upgraded acrylonitrile's classification from 'possibly carcinogenic' to carcinogenic for humans.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] The Agency found sufficient evidence linking it to lung cancer.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] In June 1974 Coca-Cola introduced the acrylonitrile/styrene 32oz Easy‐Goer plastic bottle, offering energy savings during manufacture, increased durability, and weight savings over glass.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] In March 1977 after a suit filed by the Natural Resources Defense Council the FDA rescinded approval of acrylonitrile bottles citing adverse effects on test animals.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Monsanto, Coca-Cola's bottle manufacturer, refuted the decision, stating "repeated tests have demonstrated that there is no detectable migration of acrylonitrile into the bottle's content." After several appeals in court by September 1977 the FDA finalized their ban.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] A large amount of acrylonitrile (approximately 6500 tons) leaked from an industrial polymer plant owned by Aksa Akrilik after the violent 17th August 1999 earthquake in Turkey.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Over 5000 people were affected and the exposed animals had died.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] The leak was only noticed by the company 8 hours after the incident.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Healthcare workers did not know about the health effects of acrylonitrile and tried to treat the victims with painkillers and IV fluids.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] One lawyer, Ayşe Akdemir, sued the company with 44 families as the plaintiffs.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Aksa Akrilik was sued by 200 residents who were affected by acrylonitrile.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] An increase in cancer cases in the area was confirmed by the Turkish Medical Association, as the cancer rate in the affected area has increased by 80%, from 1999 to April 2002.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] In 2003, the owner of Aksa Akrilik died from lung cancer related to acrylonitrile exposure.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Microorganisms containing nitrile hydratase enzymes (NHase) degrade harmful acrylonitrile.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Acrylonitrile has been detected at the sub-ppm level at industrial sites.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] It persists in the air for up to a week.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] It decomposes by reacting with oxygen and hydroxyl radical to form formyl cyanide and formaldehyde.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Acrylonitrile is harmful to aquatic life.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Acrylonitrile has been detected in the atmosphere of Titan, a moon of Saturn.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/acrylonitrile] Computer simulations suggest that on Titan conditions exist such that the compound could form structures similar to cell membranes and vesicles on Earth, called azotosomes.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] The **Administrative Procedure Act** (**APA**), (Pub.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] 237, enacted Jun 11, 1946, is the United States federal statute that governs the way in which administrative agencies of the federal government of the United States may propose and establish regulations, and it grants U.S. federal courts oversight over all agency actions.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] According to Hickman & Pierce, it is one of the most important pieces of United States administrative law, and serves as a sort of "constitution" for U.S. administrative law.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] The APA applies to both the federal executive departments and the independent agencies.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] U.S. senator Pat McCarran called the APA "a bill of rights for the hundreds of thousands of Americans whose affairs are controlled or regulated" by federal government agencies.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] The text of the APA can be found under Title 5 of the United States Code, beginning at Section 500.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Section 702 of the APA waives sovereign immunity, allowing people to sue a federal agency in court for non-monetary relief, such as an injunction or a declaratory judgment.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] There is a similar Model State Administrative Procedure Act (Model State APA), which was drafted by the National Conference of Commissioners on Uniform State Laws for oversight of state agencies.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Not all states have adopted the model law wholesale, as of 2017.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] The federal APA does not require systematic oversight of regulations prior to adoption, unlike the Model APA.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Each US state has passed its own version of the Administrative Procedure Act.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Beginning in 1933, President Franklin D.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Roosevelt and the Democratic Congress enacted several statutes that created new federal agencies as part of the New Deal legislative plan, established to guide the United States through the social and economic hardship caused by the Great Depression.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] However, the Congress became concerned about the expanding powers that these autonomous federal agencies now possessed, resulting in the enactment of the APA to regulate, standardize and oversee these federal agencies.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] The APA was born in a contentious political environment.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Professor George Shepard claims that Roosevelt's opponents and supporters fought over passage of the APA "in a pitched political battle for the life of the New Deal" itself.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] A 1946 House of Representatives report discusses the 10-year period of "painstaking and detailed study and drafting" that went into the APA.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Because of rapid growth in the administrative regulation of private conduct, Roosevelt ordered several studies of administrative methods and conduct during the early part of his four-term presidency.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Based on one study, Roosevelt commented that the practice of creating administrative agencies with the authority to perform both legislative and judicial work "threatens to develop a fourth branch of government for which there is no sanction in the Constitution".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] In 1939, Roosevelt requested for Attorney General Frank Murphy to form a committee to investigate practices and procedures in American administrative law and suggest improvements.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] That committee's report, the *Final Report of Attorney General's Committee on Administrative Procedure*, contained detailed information about the development and procedures of the federal agencies.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] The *Final Report* defined a federal agency as a governmental unit with "the power to determine ... private rights and obligations" by rulemaking or adjudication.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] The report applied that definition to the largest units of the federal government, and identified "nine executive departments and eighteen independent agencies".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Overall, 51 federal agencies were identified in the report after including various subdivisions within the larger units.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] In reviewing the history of federal agencies, the *Final Report* noted that almost all agencies had undergone changes in name and political function.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Of the 51 federal agencies discussed in the *Final Report*, 11 were created by statute before the American Civil War.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] From 1865 to 1900, six new agencies were created, notably the Interstate Commerce Commission in 1887 in response to widespread criticism of the railroad industry.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] From 1900 to 1930, seventeen agencies were created by statute, and eighteen more had been created since.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] The *Final Report* made several recommendations about standardizing administrative procedures, but Congress delayed action as the US entered World War II.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Five years after the report was made, Congress reintroduced the bill and President Harry S.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Truman signed the APA into law on June 11, 1946.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] In 1966, the Freedom of Information Act amended the APA to establish a system that requires federal agencies to disclose government information to the public.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] In response to the Watergate and COINTELPRO scandals, two further amendments were passed.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] The Privacy Act of 1974 amended the APA to cover the government's handling of personal information, and in 1976, the Government in the Sunshine Act further clarified what portion of government meetings and documents were required to be public.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] The Paperwork Reduction Act (1980), the Regulatory Flexibility Act (1980), and the Electronic Freedom of Information Act (1996) were further adjustments.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Although each US government agency is constituted within one branch of the government (judicial, legislative, or executive), an agency's authority often extends into the functions of other branches.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Without careful regulation, that can lead to unchecked authority in a particular area of government, violating the separation of powers, a concern that Roosevelt himself acknowledged.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] To provide constitutional safeguards, the APA creates a framework for regulating agencies and their roles.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] 4. to define the scope of judicial review.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] The APA's provisions apply to many federal governmental institutions and agencies.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Courts have also held that the U.S. president is not an agency under the APA.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] The APA's capacity to hold accountable regulatory business monitors that oversee civil matters that apply "'soft' administrative law" is also limited.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] The Supreme Court held that APA lawsuits seeking to enforce a contractual obligation to pay money must be brought in the Court of Federal Claims, not federal district courts.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] The *Final Report* organized federal administrative action into two parts: adjudication and rulemaking.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Agency adjudication was broken down further into two distinct phases of formal and informal adjudication.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Formal adjudication involve a trial-like hearing with witness testimony, a written record, and a final decision.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Under informal adjudication, agency decisions are made without these formal procedures, instead using "inspections, conferences and negotiations".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Because formal adjudication produces a record of proceedings and a final decision, it may be subject to judicial review.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] As for rulemaking resulting in agency rules and regulations, the *Final Report* noted that many agencies provided due process through hearings and investigations, but there was still a need for well-defined uniform standards for agency adjudication and rulemaking procedures.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] The APA requires that to set aside agency actions that are not subject to formal trial-like procedures (i.e. rulemaking), the court must conclude that the regulation is "arbitrary and capricious, an abuse of discretion, or otherwise not in accordance with the law".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] However, Congress may further limit the scope of judicial review of agency actions by including such language in the authorizing statute.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] To set aside formal rulemaking or formal adjudication for which procedures are trial-like, a different standard of review allows courts to question agency actions more strongly.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] For such more formal actions, agency decisions must be supported by "substantial evidence" after the court reads the "whole record", which can be thousands of pages long.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Unlike arbitrary and capricious review, substantial evidence review gives the courts leeway to consider whether an agency's factual and policy determinations were warranted in light of all the information before the agency at the time of decision.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Accordingly, arbitrary and capricious review is understood to be more deferential to agencies than substantial evidence review is.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Arbitrary and capricious review allows agency decisions to stand as long as an agency can give a reasonable explanation for its decision based on the information that it had at the time.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] By virtue of their constitutional role, U.S. presidents can try to influence specific regulatory proposals before their finalization.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Within the Executive Office of the President is the Office of Information and Regulatory Affairs (OIRA), a federal subagency led by a presidential appointee that is widely viewed as working on the president's behalf during the regulatory review process.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Rules and regulations issued or proposed (see Notice of Proposed Rulemaking) by federal administrative agencies are published chronologically in the *Federal Register*.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/administrative-procedure-act-united-states] Promulgated rules and regulations are then organized by topic in a separate publication called the Code of Federal Regulations.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Motives for action may be based on political, economic, religious, moral, commercial or common good-based positions.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Groups use varied methods to try to achieve their aims, including lobbying, media campaigns, awareness raising publicity stunts, polls, research, and policy briefings.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Some groups are supported or backed by powerful business or political interests and exert considerable influence on the political process, while others have few or no such resources.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Some have developed into important social, and political institutions or social movements.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Some powerful advocacy groups have been accused of manipulating the democratic system for narrow commercial gain, and in some instances have been found guilty of corruption, fraud, bribery, influence peddling and other serious crimes.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Some groups, generally the ones with less financial resources, may use direct action and civil disobedience, and in some cases are accused of being a threat to the social order or "domestic extremists".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Research is beginning to explore how advocacy groups use social media to facilitate civic engagement, and collective action.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] The early growth of pressure groups was connected to broad economic and political changes in England in the mid-18th century, including political representation, market capitalization, and proletarianization.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] The first mass social movement catalyzed around the controversial political figure, John Wilkes.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] As editor of the paper *The North Briton*, Wilkes vigorously attacked the new administration of Lord Bute and the peace terms that the new government accepted at the 1763 Treaty of Paris at the end of the Seven Years' War.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Charged with seditious libel, Wilkes was arrested after the issue of a general warrant, a move that Wilkes denounced as unlawful – the Lord Chief Justice eventually ruled in Wilkes favour.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] As a result of this episode, Wilkes became a figurehead to the growing movement for popular sovereignty among the middle classes – people began chanting, "Wilkes and Liberty" in the streets.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] After a later period of exile, brought about by further charges of libel and obscenity, Wilkes stood for the Parliamentary seat at Middlesex, where most of his support was located.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] This was the first ever sustained social advocacy group – it involved public meetings, demonstrations, the distribution of pamphlets on an unprecedented scale and the mass petition march.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] However, the movement was careful not to cross the line into open rebellion – it tried to rectify the faults in governance through appeals to existing legal precedents and was conceived of as an extra-Parliamentary form of agitation to arrive at a consensual and constitutional arrangement.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] The force and influence of this social advocacy movement on the streets of London compelled the authorities to concede to the movement's demands.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Wilkes was returned to Parliament, general warrants were declared as unconstitutional and press freedom was extended to the coverage of Parliamentary debates.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Another important advocacy group that emerged in the late 18th century was the British abolitionist movement against slavery.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Starting with an organised sugar boycott in 1791, it led the second great petition drive of 1806, which brought about the banning of the slave trade in 1807.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] In the opinion of Eugene Black (1963), "...association made possible the extension of the politically effective public.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Modern extra parliamentary political organization is a product of the late eighteenth century [and] the history of the age of reform cannot be written without it.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] From 1815, Britain after victory in the Napoleonic Wars entered a period of social upheaval characterised by the growing maturity of the use of social movements and special-interest associations.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Chartism was the first mass movement of the growing working-class in the world.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] It campaigned for political reform between 1838 and 1848 with the People's Charter of 1838 as its manifesto – this called for universal suffrage and the implementation of the secret ballot, amongst other things.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] The labor movement and socialist movement of the late 19th century are seen as the prototypical social movements, leading to the formation of communist and social democratic parties and organisations.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] These tendencies were seen in poorer countries as pressure for reform continued, for example in Russia with the Russian Revolution of 1905 and of 1917, resulting in the collapse of the Czarist regime around the end of the First World War.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] In the post-war period, women's rights, gay rights, peace, civil rights, anti-nuclear and environmental movements emerged, often dubbed the New Social Movements, some of which may be considered "general interest groups" as opposed to special interest groups.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] They led, among other things, to the formation of green parties and organisations influenced by the new left.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Some find in the end of the 1990s the emergence of a new global social movement, the anti-globalization movement.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Some social movement scholars posit that with the rapid pace of globalization, the potential for the emergence of new *type* of social movement is latent—they make the analogy to national movements of the past to describe what has been termed a global citizens movement.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Advocacy groups exist in a wide variety of genres based upon their most pronounced activities.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] In most liberal democracies, advocacy groups tend to use the bureaucracy as the main channel of influence – because, in liberal democracies, this is where the decision-making power lies.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] The aim of advocacy groups here is to attempt to influence a member of the legislature to support their cause by voting a certain way in the legislature.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Access to this channel is generally restricted to groups with insider status such as large corporations and trade unions – groups with outsider status are unlikely to be able to meet with ministers or other members of the bureaucracy to discuss policy.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] What must be understood about groups exerting influence in the bureaucracy is; "the crucial relationship here [in the bureaucracy] is usually that between the senior bureaucrats and leading business or industrial interests".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] This supports the view that groups with greater financial resources at their disposal will generally be better able to influence the decision-making process of government.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] The advantages that large businesses have is mainly due to the fact that they are key producers within their countries economy and, therefore, their interests are important to the government as their contributions are important to the economy.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] According to George Monbiot, the influence of big business has been strengthened by "the greater ease with which corporations can relocate production and investment in a global economy".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] This suggests that in the ever modernising world, big business has an increasing role in influencing the bureaucracy and in turn, the decision-making process of government.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Advocacy groups can also exert influence through the assembly by lobbying.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Groups with greater economic resources at their disposal can employ professional lobbyists to try and exert influence in the assembly.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] An example of such a group is the environmentalist group Greenpeace; Greenpeace (an organisation with income upward of $50,000,000) use lobbying to gain political support for their campaigns.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] They raise issues about the environment with the aim of having their issues translated into policy such as the government encouraging alternative energy and recycling.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] The judicial branch of government can also be used by advocacy groups to exert influence.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] In states where legislation cannot be challenged by the courts, like the UK, advocacy groups are limited in the amount of influence they have.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] In states that have codified constitutions, like the US, however, advocacy group influence is much more significant.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] For example, in 1954 the NAACP (National Association for the Advancement of Colored People) lobbied against the Topeka Board of education, arguing that segregation of education based on race was unconstitutional.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] As a result of group pressure from the NAACP, the supreme court unanimously ruled that racial segregation in education was indeed unconstitutional and such practices were banned.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] This is a novel example of how advocacy groups can exert influence in the judicial branch of government.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Advocacy groups can also exert influence on political parties.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] The main way groups do this is through campaign finance.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] For instance; in the UK, the conservative parties campaigns are often funded by large corporations, as many of the conservative parties campaigns reflect the interests of businesses.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Bush's re-election campaign in 2004 was the most expensive in American history and was financed mainly by large corporations and industrial interests that the Bush administration represented in government.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Conversely, left-wing parties are often funded by organised labour – when the British Labour Party was formed, it was largely funded by trade unions.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Often, political parties are actually formed as a result of group pressure, for example, the Labour Party in the UK was formed out of the new trade union movement which lobbied for the rights of workers.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Advocacy groups also exert influence through channels that are separate from the government or the political structure such as the mass media and through public opinion campaigning.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Advocacy groups will use methods such as protesting, petitioning and civil disobedience to attempt to exert influence in Liberal Democracies.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Groups will generally use two distinct styles when attempting to manipulate the media – they will either put across their outsider status and use their inability to access the other channels of influence to gain sympathy or they may put across a more ideological agenda.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Traditionally, a prime example of such a group were the trade-unions who were the so-called "industrial" muscle.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Trade-unions would campaign in the forms of industrial action and marches for workers rights, these gained much media attention and sympathy for their cause.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] In the United States, the Civil Rights Movement gained much of its publicity through civil disobedience; African Americans would simply disobey the racist segregation laws to get the violent, racist reaction from the police and white Americans.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] This violence and racism was then broadcast all over the world, showing the world just how one sided the race 'war' in America actually was.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Advocacy group influence has also manifested itself in supranational bodies that have arisen through globalisation.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Groups that already had a global structure such as Greenpeace were better able to adapt to globalisation.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Greenpeace, for example, has offices in over 30 countries and has an income of $50 million annually.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Groups such as these have secured the nature of their influence by gaining status as nongovernmental organisations (NGOs), many of which oversee the work of the UN and the EU from their permanent offices in America and Europe.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Group pressure by supranational industries can be exerted in a number of ways: "through direct lobbying by large corporations, national trade bodies and 'peak' associations such as the European Round Table of Industrialists".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Advocacy groups can influence policies away from the median voter.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] There have been many significant advocacy groups throughout history, some of which could operated with dynamics that could better categorize them as social movements.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] A general theory is that individuals must be enticed with some type of benefit to join an interest group.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] However, the free rider problem addresses the difficulty of obtaining members of a particular interest group when the benefits are already reaped without membership.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] For instance, an interest group dedicated to improving farming standards will fight for the general goal of improving farming for every farmer, even those who are not members of that particular interest group.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Thus, there is no real incentive to join an interest group and pay dues if the farmer will receive that benefit anyway.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] For another example, every individual in the world would benefit from a cleaner environment, but environmental protection interest groups do not receive monetary help from every individual in the world.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] This poses a problem for interest groups, which require dues from their members and contributions in order to accomplish the groups' agendas.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Selective benefits are material, rather than monetary benefits conferred on group members.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] For instance, an interest group could give members free or discounted travel, meals, or periodical subscriptions.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Many trade and professional interest groups tend to give these types of benefits to their members.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] A solidarity incentive is a reward for participation that is socially derived and created out of the act of association.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Examples include "socializing congeniality, the sense of group membership and identification, the status resulting from membership, fun, conviviality, the maintenance of social distinctions, and so on.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] People who join an interest group because of expressive benefits likely joined to express an ideological or moral value that they believe in, such as free speech, civil rights, economic justice, or political equality.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] To obtain these types of benefits, members would simply pay dues, and donate their time or money to get a feeling of satisfaction from expressing a political value.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Also, it would not matter if the interest group achieved their goal; these members would merely be able to say they helped out in the process of trying to obtain their goals, which is the expressive incentive that they got in the first place.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] The types of interest groups that rely on expressive benefits or incentives are environmental groups and groups who claim to be lobbying for the public interest.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Much work has been undertaken by academics attempting to categorize how advocacy groups operate, particularly in relation to governmental policy creation.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] However, this pluralist theory (formed primarily by American academics) reflects a more open and fragmented political system similar to that in countries such as the United States.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] There are three broad perspectives on how special interest groups achieve influence: through quid pro quo exchange, information transmission, and subsidizing policymaking.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Apart from lobbying and other methods of asserting political presence, advocacy groups use social media to attract attention towards their particular cause.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] A study published in early 2012 suggests that advocacy groups of varying political and ideological orientations operating in the United States are using social media to interact with citizens every day.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Another 2012 study argued that advocacy groups use social media to reach audiences unrelated to the communities they help and to mobilize diverse groups of people.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] While these studies show the acceptance of social media use by advocacy groups, populations not affiliated with media advocacy often question the benevolence of social media.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Rather than exclusively fostering an atmosphere of camaraderie and universal understanding, social media can perpetuate power hierarchies.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Since media advocacy groups use social media as a way to boost the narratives of these populations, the effect of social media use can be counteractive to well-intentioned goals.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Instead of directly amplifying the voices and narratives of historically marginalized populations, social media magnifies their concerns through the perspective of individuals with access to the internet.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] Since advocacy groups have the agency to control a community's narrative through a social media post, they have the agency to control the deservedness of a community as well.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/advocacy-group] That is, the amount of resources or attention a community receives largely depends on the kind of narrative an advocacy group curates for them on social media.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The **anti-nuclear movement** is a social movement that opposes various nuclear technologies.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Some direct action groups, environmental movements, and professional organisations have identified themselves with the movement at the local, national, or international level.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Major anti-nuclear groups include Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament, Friends of the Earth, Greenpeace, International Physicians for the Prevention of Nuclear War, Peace Action, Seneca Women's Encampment for a Future of Peace and Justice and the Nuclear Information and Resource Service.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The movement's initial objective was nuclear disarmament, though since the late 1960s, opposition has also included the use of nuclear power.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Many anti-nuclear groups oppose both nuclear power and nuclear weapons.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The formation of green parties in the 1970s and 1980s was often a direct result of anti-nuclear politics.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Scientists and diplomats have debated nuclear weapons policy since before the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki in 1945.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The public became concerned about nuclear weapons testing from about 1954, following extensive nuclear testing, including the Castle Bravo disaster.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In 1963, many countries ratified the Partial Test Ban Treaty, which prohibited atmospheric nuclear testing.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Some local opposition to nuclear power emerged in the early 1960s.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In the late 1960s some members of the scientific community began to express their concerns.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In the early 1970s, there were large protests about the proposed Wyhl Nuclear Power Plant, in southern Germany.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The project was cancelled in 1975, and anti-nuclear success at Wyhl inspired opposition to nuclear power in other parts of Europe and North America.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] A protest against nuclear power occurred in July 1977 in Bilbao, Spain, with up to 200,000 people in attendance.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Following the Three Mile Island accident in 1979, an anti-nuclear protest was held in New York City, involving 200,000 people.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In 1981, Germany's largest anti-nuclear power demonstration took place to protest against the Brokdorf Nuclear Power Plant west of Hamburg; some 100,000 people came face to face with 10,000 police officers.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The largest protest was held on 12 June 1982, when one million people demonstrated in New York City against nuclear weapons.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] A 1983 nuclear weapons protest in West Berlin had about 600,000 participants.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In May 1986, following the Chernobyl disaster, an estimated 150,000 to 200,000 people marched in Rome to protest against the Italian nuclear program.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In Australia, unions, peace activists, and environmentalists opposed uranium mining from the 1970s onwards, and rallies bringing together hundreds of thousands of people to oppose nuclear weapons peaked in the mid- 1980s.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In the US, public opposition preceded the shutdown of the Shoreham, Yankee Rowe, Millstone 1, Rancho Seco, Maine Yankee, and many other nuclear power plants.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] For many years after the 1986 Chernobyl disaster, nuclear power was off the policy agenda in most countries, and the anti-nuclear power movement seemed to have won its case, so some anti-nuclear groups disbanded.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In the 2000s, however, following public relations activities by the nuclear industry, advances in nuclear reactor designs, and concerns about climate change, nuclear power issues came back into energy policy discussions in some countries.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The 2011 Fukushima nuclear accident subsequently undermined the nuclear power industry's proposed renaissance and revived opposition to nuclear power worldwide, putting governments on the defensive.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] As of 2016, countries such as Australia, Austria, Denmark, Greece, Malaysia, New Zealand, and Norway have no nuclear power stations and remain opposed to nuclear power.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Germany, Italy, Spain, and Switzerland are phasing-out nuclear power.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Sweden formerly had a nuclear phase-out policy, aiming to end nuclear power generation in Sweden by 2010.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] On 5 February 2009, the Government of Sweden announced an agreement allowing for the replacement of existing reactors, effectively ending the phase-out policy.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Globally, the number of operable reactors has remained nearly the same over the last 30 years, and nuclear electricity production has been steadily growing since the Fukushima disaster.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The application of nuclear technology, as a source of energy and as an instrument of war, has been controversial.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] These issues are discussed in nuclear weapons debate, nuclear power debate, and uranium mining debate.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The public became concerned about nuclear weapons testing from about 1954, following extensive nuclear testing in the Pacific, with some calling it nuclear imperialism and colonialism.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In 1961, at the height of the Cold War, about 50,000 women brought together by Women Strike for Peace marched in 60 cities in the United States to demonstrate against nuclear weapons.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In 1963, many countries ratified the Partial Test Ban Treaty which prohibited atmospheric nuclear testing.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Some local opposition to nuclear power emerged in the early 1960s, and, in the late 1960s, some members of the scientific community began expressing their concerns.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In the early 1970s, there were large protests about the proposed Wyhl Nuclear Power Plant in southern Germany.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Nuclear power became an issue of major public protest in the 1970s.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The fossil fuel industry starting from the 1950s was engaging in campaigns against the nuclear industry which it perceived as a threat to their commercial interests.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Groups like the Sierra Club, Environmental Defense Fund and Natural Resources Defense Council are receiving grants from other fossil fuel companies.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] As of 2011, a strategy paper released by Greenpeace titled "Battle of Grids" proposed gradual replacement of nuclear power by fossil gas plants which would provide "flexible backup for wind and solar power".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] However, Greenpeace has since distanced itself from advocating for fossil gas, instead proposing grid energy storage as a solution to issues caused by intermittent renewable energy.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In Germany, the Energiewende, which was advertised as a shift to renewable energy but included a gradual phaseout of nuclear power from 2000 to the end of 2022, caused, among other things, a rise in fossil gas power production from 49.2 TWh in 2000 to 94.7 TWh in 2020.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In the same interval total electricity generation barely changed (576.6 TWh in 2000 vs 574.2 TWh in 2020) while it did rise and fall in the meantime, reaching a peak of 652.9 TWh in 2017.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] As much of that fossil gas was, and remains, imported from Russia, controversial pipeline projects like Nord Stream 1 were built to meet rising German gas demand.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] After the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine it came to light that significant amounts of Russian lobbying was involved in both the continued anti-nuclear movement in Germany and the anti-fracking movement.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] From an anti-nuclear point of view, there is a threat to modern civilization from global nuclear war by accidental or deliberate nuclear strike.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Some climate scientists estimate that a war between two countries that resulted in 100 Hiroshima-size atomic explosions would cause significant loss of life, in the tens of millions, from climatic effects alone, as well as disable future generations.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Soot thrown up into the atmosphere could blanket the earth, causing food chain disruption in what is termed a nuclear winter.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Ridding the world of nuclear weapons has been a cause for pacifists for decades.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] But more recently, mainstream politicians and retired military leaders have advocated nuclear disarmament.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In January 2007 an article in *The Wall Street Journal*, authored by Henry Kissinger, Bill Perry, George Shultz and Sam Nunn.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] These men were veterans of the Cold War who believed in using nuclear weapons for deterrence.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] But they now reversed their previous position and asserted that instead of making the world safer, nuclear weapons had become a source of extreme concern.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Since the 1970s, some countries have built their own second-strike capability of massive deterrence in the event of a military attack with weapons of mass destruction.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Two examples of this second-strike capability are Israel's Samson Option strategy and Russia's Dead Hand system.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] During the era of nuclear weapons testing, many local communities were affected, and some are still affected by uranium mining and radioactive waste disposal.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] It should, however, be noted that countries can possess nuclear weapons without possessing nuclear power plants (as is almost certainly the case with Israel) or indeed the reverse, as is the case with most users of nuclear power, past and present.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] There are large variations in people's beliefs regarding nuclear power, including the technology itself, its deployment, climate change, and energy security.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] There is a wide spectrum of views and concerns over nuclear power and it remains a controversial area of public policy.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] When compared to other energy sources, nuclear power has one of the lowest death rates per unit of energy produced – 0.07 per TWh, as compared to over 32 per TWh in the case of brown coal.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] This figure is driven by a 2005 WHO projection of up to 4000 stochastic cancer deaths that could result from the Chernobyl disaster.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The UNSCEAR reports in its 2008 summary on Chernobyl that no increases in cancer incidence (other than thyroid cancer) have been observed to date that can be attributed to radiation from the accident.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Many studies have shown that the public "perceives nuclear power as a very risky technology" and, around the world, nuclear energy declined in popularity in the aftermath of the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster, but it has recently rebounded in response to the climate crisis.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Anti-nuclear critics see nuclear power as a dangerous, expensive way to boil water to generate electricity.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Of these concerns, nuclear accidents and disposal of long-lived radioactive waste have probably had the greatest public impact worldwide.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Anti-nuclear campaigners point to the 2011 Fukushima nuclear emergency as proof that nuclear power can never be 100% safe.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Costs resulting from the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster are likely to exceed 12 trillion yen ($100 billion) and the clean up effort to decontaminate affected areas and decommission the plant is estimated to take 30 to 40 years.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Excluding accidents, the standard amount of high-level radioactive waste is claimed to be manageable (the UK has produced just 2150 m3 during its 60-year nuclear program), with the Geological Society of London alleging that it can be effectively recycled and stored safely.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In his book *Global Fission: The Battle Over Nuclear Power*, Jim Falk explores connections between technological concerns and political concerns.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Falk suggests that concerns of citizen groups or individuals who oppose nuclear power have often focused initially on the "range of physical hazards which accompany the technology" and lead to a "concern over the political relations of the nuclear industry".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Baruch Fischhoff, a social scientist, said that many people really do not trust the nuclear industry.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Ramana says that "distrust of the social institutions that manage nuclear energy is widespread", and a 2001 survey by the European Commission found that "only 10.1 percent of Europeans trusted the nuclear industry".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] This public distrust is periodically reinforced by nuclear safety violations or through ineffectiveness or corruption of the nuclear regulatory authorities.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Once lost, says Ramana, trust is extremely difficult to regain.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Faced with public antipathy, the nuclear industry has "tried a variety of strategies to persuade the public to accept nuclear power," including publishing numerous "fact sheets" that address public concerns.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Ramana says that none of these strategies has been very successful.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Nuclear proponents have tried to regain public support by offering newer, purportedly safer, reactor designs.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] These designs include those that incorporate passive safety and small modular reactors.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] While these reactor designs "are intended to inspire trust, they may have an unintended effect: creating distrust of older reactors that lack the touted safety features".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Since 2000 the nuclear power was promoted as potential solution to the greenhouse effect and climate change as nuclear power emits no or negligible amounts of carbon dioxide during operations.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Anti-nuclear groups highlighted that other stages of the nuclear fuel chain – mining, milling, transport, fuel fabrication, enrichment, reactor construction, decommissioning, and waste management – rely on fossil fuels and thus emit carbon dioxide.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] As this is the case with any energy sources, including renewable energy, IPCC analyzed total life-cycle greenhouse-gas emissions, which account for all emissions during manufacturing, installation, operations and decommissioning.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] With 12 gCO2eq/kWh, nuclear power remains one of the lowest-emitting energy sources available.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In 2011, a French court fined Électricité de France (EDF) €1.5m and jailed two senior employees for spying on Greenpeace, including hacking into Greenpeace's computer systems.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Greenpeace was awarded €500,000 in damages.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Some energy-related studies conclude that energy efficiency programs and renewable power technologies are better energy options than nuclear power plants.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The international nuclear fusion project, the International Thermonuclear Experimental Reactor (ITER), is constructing the world's largest and most advanced experimental tokamak nuclear fusion reactor in southern France.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] A collaboration among the European Union (EU), India, Japan, China, Russia, South Korea, and the United States, the project aims to transition from experimental studies of plasma physics to electricity-producing fusion power plants.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In 2005, Greenpeace International issued a press statement criticizing government funding of the ITER, believing the money should have been diverted to renewable energy sources and claiming that fusion energy would result in nuclear waste and nuclear weapons proliferation issues.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] A French association including about 700 anti-nuclear groups, Sortir du nucléaire (Get Out of Nuclear Energy), claimed that ITER was a hazard because scientists did not yet know how to manipulate the high-energy deuterium and tritium hydrogen isotopes used in the fusion process.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] According to most anti-nuclear groups, nuclear fusion power "remains a distant dream".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The World Nuclear Association have said that fusion "presents so far insurmountable scientific and engineering challenges".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Construction of the ITER facility began in 2007, but the project has run into many delays and budget overruns.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Several milestones of the project have already been completed, but the First Plasma completion date has been discussed and postponed multiple times, with various conclusions.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In late 2016, the ITER council agreed on an updated project schedule, with a planned First Plasma opening by 2025, nine years after the originally anticipated opening.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Some anti-nuclear groups advocate reduced reliance on reactor-produced medical radioisotopes, through the use of alternative radioisotope production and alternative clinical technologies.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Cyclotrons are being increasingly used to produce medical radioisotopes to the point where nuclear reactors are no longer needed to make the most common medical isotopes.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] However, the development of newer, more reliable and efficient particle accelerators also fuels the proposals for subcritical reactors with a Spallation Neutron Source being used for nuclear transmutation of "legacy" waste and/or power generation.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Such reactors could also be used to produce medical isotopes.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Anti-nuclear groups say that reliance on nuclear energy can be reduced by adopting energy conservation and energy efficiency measures.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Energy efficiency can reduce energy consumption while providing the same level of energy "services".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Anti-nuclear groups also favour the use of renewable energy, such as hydro, wind power, solar power, geothermal energy and biofuel.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] According to the International Energy Agency renewable energy technologies are essential contributors to the energy supply portfolio, as they contribute to world energy security and provide opportunities for mitigating greenhouse gases.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Fossil fuels are being replaced by clean, climate-stabilizing, non-depletable sources of energy.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In 2014 global wind power capacity expanded 16% to 369,553 MW.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Yearly wind energy production is also growing rapidly and has reached around 4% of worldwide electricity usage, 11.4% in the EU, and it is widely used in Asia, and the United States.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In 2014, worldwide installed photovoltaics capacity increased to 177 gigawatts (GW), sufficient to supply 1 per cent of global electricity demands.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] As of 2020 wind power expansion slowed down due to protests of residents and environmentalists.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Solar thermal energy stations operate in the United States and Spain, and as of 2016, the largest of these is the 392 MW Ivanpah Solar Electric Generating System in California.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The world's largest geothermal power installation is The Geysers in California, with a rated capacity of 750 MW.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Brazil has one of the largest renewable energy programs in the world, involving production of ethanol fuel from sugar cane, and ethanol now provides 18% of the country's automotive fuel.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Ethanol fuel is also widely available in the United States.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] As of 2020, the expansion of biomass as a fuel, which was previously praised by environmental organizations such as Greenpeace, has been criticized for environmental damage.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Greenpeace advocates reducing fossil fuel use by 50% by 2050 and phasing out nuclear power, contending that innovative technologies can increase energy efficiency and suggesting that, by 2050, most electricity will come from renewable sources.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The International Energy Agency estimates that nearly 50% of global electricity supplies will need to come from renewable energy sources to halve carbon dioxide emissions by 2050 and minimise climate change impacts.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Jacobson says producing all new energy with wind power, solar power, and hydropower by 2030 is feasible, and existing energy supply arrangements could be replaced by 2050.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Barriers to implementing the renewable energy plan are seen to be "primarily social and political, not technological or economic".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Jacobson says that energy costs with a wind, solar, and water system should be similar to today's energy costs.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] The anti-nuclear movement is a social movement which operates at the local, national, and international level.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Anti-nuclear groups have undertaken public protests and acts of civil disobedience, including occupations of nuclear plant sites.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Other salient strategies have included lobbying, petitioning government authorities, influencing public policy through referendum campaigns, and involvement in elections.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Anti-nuclear groups have also tried to influence policy implementation through litigation and by participating in licensing proceedings.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Anti-nuclear power organisations have emerged in every country that has had a nuclear power programme.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Protest movements against nuclear power first emerged in the United States at the local level and quickly spread to Europe and the rest of the world.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] National nuclear campaigns emerged in the late 1970s.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Fuelled by the Three Mile Island accident and the Chernobyl disaster, the anti-nuclear power movement mobilised political and economic forces that, for some years, "made nuclear energy untenable in many countries".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In the 1970s and 1980s, the formation of green parties was often a direct result of anti-nuclear politics (e.g., in Germany and Sweden).
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] Some of these anti-nuclear power organisations are reported to have developed considerable expertise on nuclear power and energy issues.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] In 1992, the chairman of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission said that "his agency had been pushed in the right direction on safety issues because of the pleas and protests of nuclear watchdog groups".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p01] National and local anti-nuclear groups are listed at Anti-nuclear groups in the United States and List of anti-nuclear groups.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In 1971, the town of Wyhl, on the Rhine in Southern Germany, was proposed as the site of the Wyhl Nuclear Power Plant.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In the years that followed, public opposition steadily mounted, and large protests occurred.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Television coverage of police dragging away farmers and their wives helped to turn nuclear power into a major issue.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In 1975, an administrative court withdrew the construction licence for the plant.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The Wyhl experience encouraged the formation of citizen action groups near other planned nuclear sites.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In 1972, the nuclear disarmament movement maintained a presence in the Pacific, largely in response to French nuclear testing there.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] New Zealand activists sailed boats into the test zone, interrupting the testing program.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In Australia, thousands of people joined protest marches in Adelaide, Melbourne, Brisbane, and Sydney.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Scientists issued statements demanding an end to the nuclear tests.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In Fiji, anti-nuclear activists formed an Against Testing on Mururoa organization.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In the Basque Country (Spain and France), a strong anti-nuclear movement emerged in 1973, ultimately leading to the abandonment of most planned nuclear power projects.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] On 14 July 1977, in Bilbao, between 150,000 and 200,000 people protested against the Lemoniz Nuclear Power Plant.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] This has been called the "biggest ever anti-nuclear demonstration".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In France, there were mass protests in the early 1970s, organized at nearly every planned nuclear site.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Between 1975 and 1977, some 175,000 people protested against nuclear power in ten demonstrations.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In 1977 there was a massive demonstration at the Superphénix breeder reactor in Creys-Malvillein which culminated in violence.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In West Germany, between February 1975 and April 1979, some 280,000 people were involved in seven demonstrations at nuclear sites.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Several site occupations were also attempted.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Following the Three Mile Island accident in 1979, some 120,000 people attended a demonstration against nuclear power in Bonn.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In the Philippines, there were many protests in the late 1970s and 1980s against the proposed Bataan Nuclear Power Plant, which was built but never operated due to safety concerns and issues regarding corruption.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In 1981, Germany's largest anti-nuclear power demonstration protested against the construction of the Brokdorf Nuclear Power Plant west of Hamburg.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Some 100,000 people came face-to-face with 10,000 police officers.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In the late 1970s and early 1980s, the revival of the nuclear arms race triggered a new wave of protests about nuclear weapons.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Older organizations such as the Federation of Atomic Scientists revived; newer organizations appeared, including the Nuclear Weapons Freeze Campaign and Physicians for Social Responsibility.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In the UK, on 1 April 1983, about 70,000 people linked arms to form a 14-mile-long human chain between three nuclear weapons centres in Berkshire.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] On Palm Sunday 1982, 100,000 Australians participated in anti-nuclear rallies in the nation's largest cities.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Year by year, the rallies grew, drawing 350,000 participants in 1985.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] On 29 October 1983, the Committee Cruise Missiles No organised a demonstration in The Hague, Netherlands, which was attended by 550,000 people, and was the largest demonstration in the history of the Netherlands.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In May 1986, following the Chernobyl disaster, clashes between anti-nuclear protesters and West German police were common.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] More than 400 people were injured in mid-May at demonstrations against the Wackersdorf reprocessing plant being built near Wackersdorf.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Also in May 1986, an estimated 150,000 to 200,000 people marched in Rome to protest against the Italian nuclear program, and 50,000 marched in Milan.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Hundreds of people walked from Los Angeles to Washington, D.C., in 1986 in what is referred to as the Great Peace March for Global Nuclear Disarmament.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The march took nine months to traverse 3,700 miles (6,000 km), advancing approximately fifteen miles per day.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The anti-nuclear organisation "Nevada Semipalatinsk" was formed in 1989 and was one of the first major anti-nuclear groups in the former Soviet Union.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] It attracted thousands of people to its protests and campaigns, which eventually led to the closure of the nuclear test site in north-east Kazakhstan in 1991.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The World Uranium Hearing was held in Salzburg, Austria in September 1992.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Anti-nuclear speakers from all continents, including indigenous speakers and scientists, testified to the health and environmental problems of uranium mining and processing, nuclear power, nuclear weapons, nuclear tests, and radioactive waste disposal.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] People who spoke at the 1992 Hearing included Thomas Banyacya, Katsumi Furitsu, Manuel Pino and Floyd Red Crow Westerman.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] There were many anti-nuclear protests in the United States which captured national public attention during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] These included the well-known Clamshell Alliance protests at Seabrook Station Nuclear Power Plant and the Abalone Alliance protests at Diablo Canyon Nuclear Power Plant, where thousands of protesters were arrested.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Other large protests followed the 1979 Three Mile Island accident.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] A large anti-nuclear demonstration was held in May 1979 in Washington, D.C., when 65,000 people, including the Governor of California, attended a march and rally against nuclear power.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In New York City on 23 September 1979, almost 200,000 people attended a protest against nuclear power.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Anti-nuclear power protests preceded the shutdown of the Shoreham, Yankee Rowe, Millstone I, Rancho Seco, Maine Yankee, and about a dozen other nuclear power plants.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] On 12 June 1982, one million people demonstrated in New York City's Central Park against nuclear weapons and for an end to the cold war arms race.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] It was the largest anti-nuclear protest and the largest political demonstration in American history.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] International Day of Nuclear Disarmament protests were held on 20 June 1983, at 50 sites across the United States.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In 1986, hundreds of people walked from Los Angeles to Washington, D.C., in the Great Peace March for Global Nuclear Disarmament.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] There were many Nevada Desert Experience protests and peace camps at the Nevada Test Site during the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] On 1 May 2005, 40,000 anti-nuclear/anti-war protesters marched past the United Nations in New York, 60 years after the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] This was the largest anti-nuclear rally in the U.S. for several decades.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In the 2000s, there were protests about, and campaigns against, several new nuclear reactor proposals in the United States.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In 2013, four aging, uncompetitive, reactors were permanently closed: San Onofre 2 and 3 in California, Crystal River 3 in Florida, and Kewaunee in Wisconsin.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Vermont Yankee, in Vernon, is scheduled to close in 2014, following many protests.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Protesters in New York State are seeking to close Indian Point Energy Center, in Buchanan, 30 miles from New York City.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] For many years after the 1986 Chernobyl disaster, nuclear power was off the policy agenda in most countries, and the anti-nuclear power movement seemed to have won its case.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In the 2000s (decade), however, following public relations activities by the nuclear industry, advances in nuclear reactor designs, and concerns about climate change, nuclear power issues came back into energy policy discussions in some countries.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster subsequently undermined the nuclear power industry's proposed comeback.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In January 2004, up to 15,000 anti-nuclear protesters marched in Paris against a new generation of nuclear reactors, the European Pressurised Water Reactor (EPWR).
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In Britain, there were many protests about the government's proposal to replace the aging Trident weapons system with a newer model.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The largest protest had 100,000 participants and, according to polls, 59 per cent of the public opposed the move.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] On 17 March 2007, simultaneous protests, organised by *Sortir du nucléaire*, were staged in five French towns to protest construction of EPR plants; Rennes, Lyon, Toulouse, Lille, and Strasbourg.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In June 2007, 4,000 residents, students, and anti-nuclear activists took to the streets in the city of Kudus in Indonesia's Central Java, calling on the Government to abandon plans to build a nuclear power plant there.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In February 2008, a group of concerned scientists and engineers called for the closure of the Kazantzakis-Kariwa Nuclear Power Plant in Japan.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The International Conference on Nuclear Disarmament took place in Oslo in February 2008.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The Government of Norway, the Nuclear Threat Initiative, and the Hoover Institute organized it.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The Conference was entitled *Achieving the Vision of a World Free of Nuclear Weapons* and had the purpose of building consensus between nuclear weapon states and non-nuclear weapon states in relation to the Nuclear Non-proliferation Treaty.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] During a weekend in October 2008, some 15,000 people disrupted the transport of radioactive nuclear waste from France to a dump in Germany.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] This was one of the largest such protests in many years and, according to *Der Spiel*, it signals a revival of the anti-nuclear movement in Germany.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In 2009, the coalition of green parties in the European parliament, who are unanimous in their anti-nuclear position, increased their presence in the parliament from 5.5% to 7.1% (52 seats).
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In October 2008, in the United Kingdom, more than 30 people were arrested during one of the largest anti-nuclear protests at the Atomic Weapons Establishment at Aldermaston for 10 years.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The demonstration marked the start of the UN World Disarmament Week and involved about 400 people.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In 2008 and 2009, there have been protests about, and criticism of, several new nuclear reactor proposals in the United States.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] There have also been some objections to license renewals for existing nuclear plants.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] A convoy of 350 farm tractors and 50,000 protesters took part in an anti-nuclear rally in Berlin on 5 September 2009.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The marchers demanded that Germany close all nuclear plants by 2020 and close the Gorleben radioactive dump.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Gorleben is the focus of the anti-nuclear movement in Germany, which has tried to derail train transports of waste and to destroy or block the approach roads to the site.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Two above-ground storage units house 3,500 containers of radioactive sludge and thousands of tonnes of spent fuel rods.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] On 21 April 2010, a dozen environmental organizations called on the United States Nuclear Regulatory Commission to investigate possible limitations in the AP1000 reactor design.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] These groups appealed to three federal agencies to suspend the licensing process, arguing that containment in the new design is weaker than in existing reactors.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] On 24 April 2010, about 120,000 people built a human chain (KETTENreAKTION!) between the nuclear plants at Krümmel and Brunsbüttel.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In this way, they were demonstrating against the German government's plans to extend the lifespans of nuclear power reactors.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In May 2010, some 25,000 people, including members of peace organizations and 1945 atomic bomb survivors, marched for about two kilometers from downtown New York to the United Nations headquarters, calling for the elimination of nuclear weapons.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In September 2010, German government policy shifted back toward nuclear energy, and this generated some new anti-nuclear sentiment in Berlin and beyond.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] On 18 September 2010, tens of thousands of Germans surrounded Chancellor Angela Merkel's office in an anti-nuclear demonstration that organisers said was the biggest of its kind since the 1986 Chernobyl disaster.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In October 2010, tens of thousands of people protested in Munich against the nuclear power policy of Angela Merkel's coalition government.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The action was the largest anti-nuclear event in Bavaria for more than two decades.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In November 2010, there were violent protests against a train carrying reprocessed nuclear waste in Germany.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Tens of thousands of protesters gathered in Dannenberg to signal their opposition to the cargo.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Around 16,000 police were mobilised to deal with the protests.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In December 2010, some 10,000 people (mainly fishermen, farmers, and their families) turned out to oppose the Jaitapur Nuclear Power Project in the Maharashtra state of India, amid a heavy police presence.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In December 2010, five anti-nuclear weapons activists, including octogenarians and Jesuit priests, were convicted of conspiracy and trespass in Tacoma, US.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] They cut fences at Naval Base Kitsap-Bangor in 2009 to protest submarine nuclear weapons, and reached an area near where Trident nuclear warheads are stored in bunkers.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Members of the group could face up to 10 years in prison.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In January 2011, five Japanese young people held a hunger strike for more than a week, outside the Prefectural Government offices in Yamaguchi City, to protest against the planned Kaminoseki Nuclear Power Plant near the environmentally sensitive Seto Inland Sea.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Following the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster, anti-nuclear opposition intensified in Germany.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] On 12 March 2011, 60,000 Germans formed a 45-km human chain from Stuttgart to the Neckarwestheim power plant.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] On 14 March 110,000 people protested in 450 other German towns, with opinion polls indicating 80% of Germans opposed the government's extension of nuclear power.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] On 15 March 2011, Angela Merkel said that seven nuclear power plants which went online before 1980 would be closed and the time would be used to study speedier renewable energy commercialization.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In March 2011, around 2,000 anti-nuclear protesters demonstrated in Taiwan for an immediate halt to the construction of the island's fourth nuclear power plant.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The protesters were also opposed to plans to extend the lifespan of three existing nuclear plants.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In March 2011, more than 200,000 people took part in anti-nuclear protests in four large German cities, on the eve of state elections.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Organisers called it the largest anti-nuclear demonstration the country has seen.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Thousands of Germans demanding an end to the use of nuclear power took part in nationwide demonstrations on 2 April 2011.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] About 7,000 people took part in anti-nuclear protests in Bremen.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] About 3,000 people protested outside RWE's headquarters in Essen.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Citing the Fukushima nuclear disaster, environmental activists at a U.N. meeting in April 2011 "urged bolder steps to tap renewable energy so the world doesn't have to choose between the dangers of nuclear power and the ravages of climate change".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In mid-April, 17,000 people protested at two demonstrations in Tokyo against nuclear power.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In India, environmentalists, local farmers and fishermen have been protesting for months over the planned Jaitapur Nuclear Power Project six-reactor complex, 420 km south of Mumbai.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] If built, it would be one of the world's largest nuclear power complexes.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Protests have escalated following Japan's Fukushima nuclear disaster, and during two days of violent rallies in April 2011, a local man was killed, and dozens were injured.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In May 2011, some 20,000 people turned out for Switzerland's largest anti-nuclear power demonstration in 25 years.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Demonstrators marched peacefully near the Beznau Nuclear Power Plant, Switzerland's oldest nuclear power plant, which began operating 40 years ago.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Days after the anti-nuclear rally, Cabinet decided to ban the building of new nuclear power reactors.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The country's five existing reactors would be allowed to continue operating, but "would not be replaced at the end of their life span".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In May 2011, 5,000 people joined a carnival-like anti-nuclear protest in Taipei City.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] This was part of a nationwide "No Nuke Action" protest, urging the government to stop construction of a Fourth Nuclear Plant and pursue a more sustainable energy policy.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] On World Environment Day in June 2011, environmental groups demonstrated against Taiwan's nuclear power policy.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The Taiwan Environmental Protection Union, together with 13 environmental groups and legislators, gathered in Taipei to protest the nation's three operating nuclear power plants and the construction of a fourth.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Three months after the Fukushima nuclear disaster, thousands of anti-nuclear protesters marched in Japan.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In August 2011, about 2,500 people, including farmers and fishermen, marched in Tokyo.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] They are suffering heavy losses following the Fukushima nuclear disaster and have called for prompt compensation from the plant operator, TEPCO, and the government.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Protesters called for a complete shutdown of Japanese nuclear power plants and demanded a shift in government policy toward alternative sources of energy.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Among the protestors were four young men who started a 10-day hunger strike to bring about change in Japan's nuclear policy.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Tens of thousands of people marched in central Tokyo in September 2011, chanting "Sayonara nuclear power" and waving banners, to call on Japan's government to abandon atomic energy in the wake of the Fukushima nuclear disaster.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Author Kenzaburō Ōe and musician Ryuichi Sakamoto were among the event's supporters.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Since the March 2011 Japanese Fukushima nuclear disaster, "populations around proposed Indian NPP sites have launched protests that are now finding resonance around the country, raising questions about atomic energy as a clean and safe alternative to fossil fuels".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Assurances by Prime Minister Manmohan Singh that all safety measures will be implemented, have not been heeded.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] There have thus been mass protests against the French-backed 9900 MW Jaitapur Nuclear Power Project in Maharashtra and the 2000 MW Koodankulam Nuclear Power Plant in Tamil Nadu.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The state government of West Bengal has also refused permission for a proposed 6,000 MW facility in which six Russian reactors were to be built.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] A Public Interest Litigation (PIL) has also been filed against the government's civil nuclear program at the apex Supreme Court.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The PIL specifically asks for the "staying of all proposed nuclear power plants till satisfactory safety measures and cost-benefit analyses are completed by independent agencies".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Michael Banach, the current Vatican representative to the International Atomic Energy Agency, told a conference in Vienna in September 2011 that the Japanese nuclear disaster created new concerns about the safety of nuclear plants globally.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Auxiliary bishop of Osaka Michael Goro Matsuura said this serious nuclear power incident should be a lesson for Japan and other countries to abandon nuclear projects.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] He called on the worldwide Christian solidarity to provide wide support for this anti-nuclear campaign.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Statements from bishops' conferences in Korea and the Philippines called on their governments to abandon atomic power.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Nobel laureate Kenzaburō Ōe has said that Japan should quickly decide to abandon its nuclear reactors.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In the UK, in October 2011, more than 200 protesters blockaded the Hinkley Point C nuclear power station site.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Members of the Stop New Nuclear alliance barred access to the site in protest of EDF Energy's plans to build two new reactors there.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In January 2012, 22 South Korean women's groups appealed for a nuclear-free future, saying they believe nuclear weapons and power reactors "threaten our lives, the lives of our families and all living creatures".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The women said they feel an enormous sense of crisis after the Fukushima nuclear disaster in March 2011, which demonstrated the destructive power of radiation in the disruption of human lives, environmental pollution, and food contamination.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Thousands of demonstrators took to the streets of Yokohama, Japan, on 14–15 January 2012, to show their support for a nuclear power-free world.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The demonstration showed that organized opposition to nuclear power has gained momentum following the Fukushima nuclear disaster.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The most immediate demand of the demonstrators was for the protection of rights, including basic human rights such as health care, for those affected by the Fukushima accident.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In January 2012, three hundred anti-nuclear protestors marched against plans to build a new nuclear power station at Wylfa in the UK.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The march was organised by Pobl Atal Wylfa B, Greenpeace, and Cymdeithas yr Iaith, which are supporting a farmer who is in dispute with Horizon.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] On the anniversary of the 11 March earthquake and tsunami, protesters across Japan called for the abolition of nuclear power and nuclear reactors.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In Koriyama, Fukushima, 16,000 people called for the end of nuclear power.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In Shizuoka Prefecture, 1,100 people appealed for the scrapping of the Hamaoka Nuclear Power Plant.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In Tsuruga, Fukui, 1,200 people marched in the streets of the city of Tsuruga, the home of the Monju fast-breeder reactor prototype and other nuclear reactors.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In Nagasaki and Hiroshima, anti-nuclear protesters and atomic-bomb survivors marched together and demanded that Japan end its nuclear dependency.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Austrian Chancellor Werner Faymann expects anti-nuclear petition drives to start in at least six European Union countries in 2012 in an effort to have the EU abandon nuclear power.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Under the EU's Lisbon Treaty, petitions that attract at least one million signatures can prompt the European Commission to propose legislation, paving the way for anti-nuclear activists to garner support.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In March 2012, about 2,000 people staged an anti-nuclear protest in Taiwan's capital following the massive tsunami that hit Japan one year ago.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The protesters rallied in Taipei to renew calls for a nuclear-free island.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] They "want the government to scrap a plan to operate a newly constructed nuclear power plant – the fourth in densely populated Taiwan".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Scores of aboriginal protesters "demanded the removal of 100,000 barrels of nuclear waste stored on their Orchid Island".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In March 2012, hundreds of anti-nuclear demonstrators converged on the Australian headquarters of global mining giants BHP Billiton and Rio Tinto.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The 500-strong march through southern Melbourne called for an end to uranium mining in Australia.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] It included speeches and performances by representatives of the expatriate Japanese community as well as Australia's Indigenous communities, who are concerned about the effects of uranium mining near tribal lands.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In March 2012, South Korean environmental groups held a rally in Seoul to oppose nuclear power.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Over 5,000 people attended, and the turnout was one of the largest in recent memory for an anti-nuclear rally.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The demonstration demanded that President Lee Myung-bak abandon his policy of promoting nuclear power.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In March 2012, police said they had arrested nearly 200 anti-nuclear activists who were protesting the restart of work at the long-stalled Indian Kudankulam nuclear power plant.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In June 2012, tens of thousands of Japanese protesters participated in anti-nuclear power rallies in Tokyo and Osaka, over the government's decision to restart the first idled reactors since the Fukushima disaster, at Oi Nuclear Power Plant in Fukui Prefecture.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Thousands of protesters marched in Tokyo on 11 March 2013, calling on the government to reject nuclear power.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In March 2013, 68,000 Taiwanese protested across major cities against nuclear power and the island's fourth nuclear plant, which is under construction.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Taiwan's three existing nuclear plants are near the ocean and prone to geological fractures under the island.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In April 2013, thousands of Scottish campaigners, MSPs, and union leaders rallied against nuclear weapons.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The Scrap Trident Coalition wants to see an end to nuclear weapons and says saved money should be used for health, education, and welfare initiatives.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] There was also a blockade of the Faslane Naval Base, where Trident missiles are stored.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In March 2014, around 130,000 Taiwanese marched in an anti-nuclear protest around Taiwan.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] They demanded that the government remove nuclear power plants in Taiwan.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The march came ahead of the 3rd anniversary of the Fukushima disaster.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Around 50,000 people marched in Taipei, while three separate events were held in other Taiwanese cities, each attended by around 30,000 people.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Among the participants are the organizations from Green Citizen Action's Alliance, Homemakers United Foundation, Taiwan Association for Human Rights and Taiwan Environmental Protection Union.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Facing ongoing opposition and a host of delays, construction of the Lungmen Nuclear Power Plant was halted in April 2014.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Beginning in the 1950s, anti-nuclear ideas received coverage in the popular media with novels such as *Fail-Safe* and feature films such as *Godzilla (1954),* *Dr.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Strangelove or: How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Bomb* (1964), *The China Syndrome* (1979), *Silkwood* (1983), and *The Rainbow Warrior* (1992).
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Musicians United for Safe Energy (MUSE) was a musical group founded in 1979 by Jackson Browne, Graham Nash, Bonnie Raitt, and John Hall, following the Three Mile Island nuclear accident.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The group organized a series of five *No Nukes* concerts held at Madison Square Garden in New York City in September 1979.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] On 23 September 1979, almost 200,000 people attended a large anti-nuclear rally staged by MUSE on the then-empty north end of the Battery Park City landfill in New York.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The album *No Nukes*, and a film, also titled *No Nukes*, were both released in 1980 to document the performances.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In 2007, Bonnie Raitt, Graham Nash, and Jackson Browne, as part of the No Nukes group, recorded a music video of the Buffalo Springfield song "For What It's Worth".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Filmmakers Taylor Dunne and Eric Stewart are working on a documentary called "Off Country" that looks at the devastating effects of atomic bomb testing on the communities around the White Sands missile range in New Mexico, the Nevada Test Site, and the Rocky Flats Plant in Colorado.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] They were interviewed by Screen Comment's Sam Weisberg in 2017.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The *Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists* is a nontechnical online magazine that has been published continuously since 1945, when it was founded by former Manhattan Project physicists after the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The *Bulletin*'s primary aim is to inform the public about nuclear policy debates while advocating for the international control of nuclear weapons.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] One of the driving forces behind the creation of the *Bulletin* was the public interest in atomic energy at the dawn of the atomic age.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In 1945 the public interest in atomic warfare and weaponry inspired contributors to the *Bulletin* to attempt to inform those interested about the dangers and destruction that atomic war could bring about.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In the 1950s, the *Bulletin* was involved in the formation of the Pugwash Conferences on Science and World Affairs, annual conferences of scientists concerned about nuclear proliferation.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Wittner has argued that anti-nuclear sentiment and activism led directly to government policy shifts about nuclear weapons.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Public opinion influenced policymakers by limiting their options and forcing them to choose certain policies over others.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Wittner credits public pressure and anti-nuclear activism with "Truman's decision to explore the Baruch Plan, Eisenhower's efforts towards a nuclear test ban and the 1958 testing moratorium, and Kennedy's signing of the Partial Test Ban Treaty".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Between 1975 and 1980, a total of 63 nuclear units were canceled in the United States.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Anti-nuclear activities were among the reasons, but the primary motivations were the overestimation of future electricity demand and steadily rising capital costs, which made the economics of new plants unfavorable.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The proliferation of nuclear weapons became a presidential priority issue for the Carter Administration in the late 1970s.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] To deal with proliferation problems, President Carter promoted stronger international control over nuclear technology, including nuclear reactor technology.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Although a strong supporter of nuclear power generally, Carter turned against the breeder reactor because the plutonium it produced could be diverted into nuclear weapons.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] For many years after the 1986 Chernobyl disaster, nuclear power was off the policy agenda in most countries.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In recent years, intense public relations activities by the nuclear industry, increasing evidence of climate change and failures to address it, have brought nuclear power issues back to the forefront of policy discussion in the nuclear renaissance countries.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] But some countries are not prepared to expand nuclear power and are still divesting themselves of their nuclear legacy, through nuclear power phase-out legislation.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Under the *New Zealand Nuclear Free Zone, Disarmament, and Arms Control Act 1987*, all territorial sea and land of New Zealand is declared a nuclear free zone.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Nuclear-powered and nuclear-armed ships are prohibited from entering the country's territorial waters.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Dumping of foreign radioactive waste and development of nuclear weapons in the country are outlawed.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] This followed a decades-long campaign by peace activists, which included disrupting US warship visits.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Despite common misconception, this act does not make nuclear power plants illegal, nor does it make radioactive medical treatments produced in overseas reactors illegal.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] A 2008 survey shows that 19% of New Zealanders favour nuclear power as the best energy source, while 77% prefer wind power as the best energy source.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] On 26 February 1990, FW de Klerk issued orders to terminate the country's nuclear weapons programme, which until then had been a state secret.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] South Africa becomes the first country in the world to voluntary give-up its nuclear weapons programme.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Ireland, in 1999, had no plans to change its non-nuclear stance and pursue nuclear power in the future.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In the United States, the Navajo Nation forbids uranium mining and processing in its land.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Given the unpopularity of nuclear weapons, U.S. politicians have been wary of supporting new nuclear programs.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The Megatons to Megawatts Program converts weapons-grade material from nuclear warheads into fuel for nuclear power plants.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Thirty-one countries operate nuclear power plants.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] During Barack Obama's successful U.S. presidential election campaign, he advocated the abolition of nuclear weapons.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Since his election, he has reiterated this goal in several major policy addresses.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In 2010, the Obama administration negotiated a new weapons accord with Russia for a reduction of the maximum number of deployed nuclear weapons on each side from 2,200 to between 1,500 and 1,675—a reduction of some 30 per cent.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In addition, President Obama has committed $15 billion over the next five years to improving the safety of the nuclear weapons stockpile.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Following the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster, the Italian government put a one-year moratorium on plans to revive nuclear power.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] On 11–12 June 2011, Italian voters passed a referendum to cancel plans for new reactors.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Over 94% of the electorate voted in favor of the construction ban, with 55% of the eligible voters participating, making the vote binding.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] German Chancellor Angela Merkel's coalition announced on 30 May 2011, that Germany's 17 nuclear power stations will be shut down by 2022, in a policy reversal following Japan's Fukushima I nuclear accidents and anti-nuclear protests within Germany.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Seven of the German power stations were temporarily closed in March and will remain offline and be permanently decommissioned.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] An eighth was already offline, and will stay so.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] As of 2011, countries such as Australia, Austria, Denmark, Greece, Ireland, Italy, Latvia, Liechtenstein, Luxembourg, Malta, Portugal, Israel, Malaysia, New Zealand, and Norway remain opposed to nuclear power.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Germany, Switzerland and Belgium are phasing-out nuclear power.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In 2005, the International Atomic Energy Agency presented the results of a series of public opinion surveys in the *Global Public Opinion on Nuclear Issues* report.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Majorities of respondents in 14 of the 18 countries surveyed believed that the risk of terrorist acts involving radioactive materials at nuclear facilities is high, because of insufficient protection.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] While a majority of citizens supported the continued use of existing nuclear power reactors, most did not favor building new nuclear plants, and 25% of respondents felt that all nuclear power plants should be closed down.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Stressing the climate change benefits of nuclear energy increases support for expanding the role of nuclear power in the world by 10%; however, there is still a general reluctance to support building more nuclear power plants.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] There was little support worldwide for building new nuclear reactors, a 2011 BBC poll indicated.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The global research agency GlobeScan, commissioned by BBC News, polled 23,231 people in 23 countries from July to September 2011, several months after the Fukushima nuclear disaster.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In countries with existing nuclear programmes, people are significantly more opposed to them than they were in 2005, with only the UK and the US bucking the trend.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Most believed that boosting energy efficiency and renewable energy can meet their needs.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The Eurobarometer 2008 poll indicated that 44% supported and 45% opposed nuclear energy in the European Union.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The majority (over 62%) also appreciated nuclear power as a means to prevent climate change.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Both Eurobarometer and subsequent OECD poll (2010) indicated a "clear correlation between knowledge and support", so respondents who were more aware of the greenhouse gas emissions from energy sector were more likely to support low-emission nuclear power.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] A 2012 meta-analysis also confirmed positive correlation between support for nuclear power and understanding of nuclear power operations, with a significant effect where people living closer to nuclear power plant showed higher levels of support in general.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In the United States, support and opposition to nuclear power plants is split almost equally.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Attempts to reach political agreement on effective climate change policies continue, and pro-nuclear environmentalists seek to reverse the traditionally anti-nuclear attitudes among environmentalists.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Filmmaker Rob Stone's *Pandora's Promise* (2013) is a good example of this trend.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Some environmentalists criticise the anti-nuclear movement for understating the environmental costs of fossil fuels and non-nuclear alternatives, and overstating the environmental costs of nuclear energy.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Anti-nuclear activists are accused of encouraging radiophobic emotions among the public.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In *The War Against the Atom* (Basic Books, 1982), Samuel MacCracken of Boston University argued that in 1982, 50,000 deaths per year could be attributed directly to non-nuclear power plants, if fuel production and transportation, as well as pollution, were taken into account.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] He argued that if non-nuclear plants were judged by the same standards as nuclear ones, each US non-nuclear power plant could be held responsible for about 100 deaths per year.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The Nuclear Energy Institute (NEI) is the main lobby group for companies doing nuclear work in the United States, while most countries that employ nuclear energy have a national industry group.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] The World Nuclear Association is the only global trade body.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] In seeking to counter the arguments of nuclear opponents, it cites independent studies that quantify the costs and benefits of nuclear energy and compares them with those of alternatives.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] NEI sponsors studies of its own, but it also references studies performed for the World Health Organization, for the International Energy Agency, and by university researchers.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Critics of the anti-nuclear movement point to independent studies showing that the capital resources required for renewable energy sources are often prohibitively higher than those for nuclear power.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Some people, including former opponents of nuclear energy, criticize the movement, arguing that nuclear power is necessary to reduce carbon dioxide emissions.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] These individuals include James Lovelock, originator of the Gaia hypothesis, Patrick Moore, an early member of Greenpeace and former director of Greenpeace International, George Monbiot and Stewart Brand, creator of the Whole Earth Catalog.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Lovelock goes further to refute claims about the danger of nuclear energy and its waste products.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Some anti-nuclear organisations have acknowledged that their positions are subject to review.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] George Monbiot, an English writer known for his environmental and political activism, once expressed deep antipathy to the nuclear industry.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] He finally rejected his later neutral position regarding nuclear power in March 2011.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/anti-nuclear-movement-p02] Monbiot now advocates its use, having been convinced of its relative safety by what he considers the limited effects of the 2011 Japan tsunami on nuclear reactors in the region.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] The **Natural Resources Defense Council** (**NRDC**) is a United States–based 501(c)(3) nonprofit international environmental advocacy group, with its headquarters in New York City and offices in Washington, D.C., San Francisco, Los Angeles, Chicago, Bozeman, India, and Beijing.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] The group was founded in 1970 in opposition to a hydroelectric power plant in New York.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] As of 2019, the NRDC had over three million members, with online activities nationwide, and a staff of about 700 lawyers, scientists and other policy experts.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] Its establishment was partially an outgrowth of the *Scenic Hudson Preservation Conference v.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] Federal Power Commission*, the Storm King case.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] The case centered on Con Ed's plan to build the world's largest hydroelectric facility at Storm King Mountain in New York's Hudson Valley.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] The proposed facility would have pumped vast amounts of water from the Hudson River to a reservoir and released it through turbines to generate electricity at peak demand.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] Adams was the group's first staff member and Duggan its founding chairman; Seymour, Laurance Rockefeller, and others served as members of the board.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] The FDA reported that test animals exposed to acrylonitrile had "significantly lowered body weight and other adverse effects, including lesions in the central nervous system and growths in the ear ducts." and suspended its approval.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] In the 1970s, NRDC sought to block expansion of the Indian Point nuclear power plant in New York.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] It had advocated for the closure of the plant until it ceased operations in 2021.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] NRDC has also sought to close the Diablo Canyon nuclear plant in California.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] In 2018, the NRDC took no position on legislative proposals in New Jersey to subsidize three of its nuclear reactors.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] NRDC has argued that nuclear power is not a viable energy source to mitigate climate change, arguing that it poses public health and safety risks through nuclear waste and nuclear proliferation.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] In 2014, NRDC president Frances Beinecke said that the NRDC could not support nuclear power because it would lose donations.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] According to NRDC, rooftop solar power plays an "essential role... in our shared mission to confront the climate crisis." However, its activism on rooftop solar has sparked controversy.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] In 2022, NRDC called for reductions in subsidies for rooftop solar power in California, prompting criticism of NRDC by other environmental groups.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] In 2012, NRDC sued the federal government to stop the 663.5-megawatt Calico solar station in the Mojave Desert in California.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] NRDC said the solar plant would imperil protected wildlife.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] NRDC's position on hydropower is that it is not a renewable energy source.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] When Indian Point was scheduled for closure, NRDC held no position on a proposal to build a transmission line to Quebec to access excess hydropower while arguing, "we certainly would not be on board where [hydropower] gobbles up the space we think should be covered by true renewables".
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] As a legal advocacy group, the NRDC works to accomplish environmental goals by operating within the legal system to reduce pollution and protect natural resources through litigation, and by working with professionals in science, law, and policy at the national and international level.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] The NRDC's Center for Campaigns & Organizing (CC&O) also oversees the NRDC Action Fund, a separate 501(c)(4) nonprofit organization which engages in political and electoral activities.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] NRDC published *onEarth*, a quarterly magazine that dealt with environmental challenges, through 2016.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] It was founded in 1979 as *The Amicus Journal*.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] As *Amicus*, it won the George Polk Award in 1983 for special interest reporting.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] The council's first president was John H.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] He was replaced by Frances Beinecke, who served as president from 2006 to 2015.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] The third president was Rhea Suh, who served from 2015 to 2019.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] In 2020, Gina McCarthy served as the CEO and president.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] She previously served as the head of the Environmental Protection Agency in the Obama administration and became White House National Climate Advisor in the Biden administration in 2021.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] In 2021, NRDC selected Manish Bapna, formerly of the World Resources Institute, as their new president and CEO.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] At their web site NRDC state they have about 700 employees including scientists, lawyers, and policy advocates.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] NRDC opposed the Water Rights Protection Act, a bill that would prevent federal agencies from requiring certain entities to relinquish their water rights to the United States in order to use public lands.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] NRDC supported the EPS Service Parts Act of 2014 (H.R.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] 5057; 113th Congress), a bill that would exempt certain external power supplies from complying with standards set forth in a final rule published by the United States Department of Energy in February 2014.
[src:natural-resources-defense-council/natural-resources-defense-council] NRDC has been involved in the following Supreme Court cases interpreting United States administrative law.
